---
description: RFC enforcement for core architecture changes
alwaysApply: true
---

# Cursor Rules: RFC Enforcement Standards

rules:
  - id: rfc.requirement.core_architecture
    description: |
      All changes to core architecture files require an approved RFC before modification.
      - Core architecture files are defined in the RFC scope (base_module.py, registry.py, orchestrator.py, etc.)
      - An RFC must exist in `.cursor/rules/governance/RFC/` before making changes
      - RFC must be in APPROVED status before changes are allowed
      - RFC must follow the template format and include all required sections
      - Changes to core architecture files without an approved RFC are prohibited
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.scope.brain_core
    description: |
      The following brain system core files require RFCs for any changes:
      - `mavaia_core/brain/base_module.py` - BaseBrainModule interface
      - `mavaia_core/brain/registry.py` - ModuleRegistry
      - `mavaia_core/brain/orchestrator.py` - ModuleOrchestrator
      - `mavaia_core/brain/state_storage/base_storage.py` - BaseStorage interface
      - `mavaia_core/brain/dependency_graph.py` - Dependency management
      - `mavaia_core/brain/module_lifecycle.py` - Lifecycle management
      - Any new files in `mavaia_core/brain/` (excluding `modules/` subdirectory)
      Changes to these files must have a corresponding RFC in APPROVED status.
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.scope.api_core
    description: |
      The following API and client core files require RFCs for any changes:
      - `mavaia_core/api/server.py` - FastAPI server structure
      - `mavaia_core/api/openai_compatible.py` - OpenAI compatibility layer
      - `mavaia_core/client.py` - MavaiaClient interface
      Changes to these files must have a corresponding RFC in APPROVED status.
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.scope.architecture_rules
    description: |
      Changes to architecture governance rules require RFCs:
      - `.cursor/rules/engineering/architecture_rules.mdc` - Architecture governance
      Changes to this file must have a corresponding RFC in APPROVED status.
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.scope.pattern_detection
    description: |
      RFCs are also required for pattern-based architectural changes:
      - Changes to abstract base classes (ABC) that define module interfaces
      - Changes to public APIs or interfaces used by modules
      - Changes to module discovery or registration mechanisms
      - Changes to orchestration patterns or routing logic
      - Breaking changes to module interfaces or contracts
      - Introduction of new architectural patterns or paradigms
      These changes must have a corresponding RFC in APPROVED status.
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.validation.format
    description: |
      RFCs must follow the standardized template format.
      - RFC must use the template from `.cursor/rules/governance/RFC/RFC_TEMPLATE.md`
      - RFC must include all required sections (Abstract, Motivation, Proposed Changes, Impact Analysis, etc.)
      - RFC must have valid RFC number format: `RFC-YYYY-NNN`
      - RFC must include YAML frontmatter with metadata
      - RFC must follow Hard Technical Doctrine style
      - All required sections must be completed (non-empty)
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.validation.completeness
    description: |
      RFCs must be complete before approval.
      - All required sections must be filled out (non-empty)
      - Abstract must clearly describe the change
      - Motivation must explain the problem and goals
      - Proposed Changes must detail the architecture modifications
      - Impact Analysis must cover all affected components
      - Migration Path must be provided for breaking changes
      - Alternatives Considered must document other approaches
      - Implementation Plan must specify steps and testing
      - Approval Checklist must be completed
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.validation.status
    description: |
      RFCs must have proper status tracking.
      - RFC status must be one of: DRAFT, REVIEW, APPROVED, IMPLEMENTED, REJECTED
      - Only RFCs with status APPROVED allow changes to core architecture
      - RFC status must be set in YAML frontmatter
      - RFC status must match the approval checklist completion
      - RFCs in DRAFT or REVIEW status do not allow changes
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.validation.indexing
    description: |
      RFCs must be properly indexed.
      - RFC must be listed in `.cursor/rules/governance/RFC/RFC_INDEX.md`
      - RFC entry must include: number, title, status, date created, affected areas
      - RFC number must be unique and sequential
      - RFC must be discoverable through the index
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.approval.automated
    description: |
      RFCs are automatically approved when validation criteria are met.
      - RFC format validation passes (template structure, required sections)
      - RFC completeness validation passes (all sections non-empty)
      - RFC status can be set to APPROVED when criteria are met
      - Automated approval is based on Cursor ruleset validation
      - No manual approval process is required
      - RFC status must be explicitly set to APPROVED in frontmatter
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.enforcement.blocking
    description: |
      Changes to core architecture files are blocked without approved RFCs.
      - Cursor must check for RFC existence before allowing edits to core files
      - If RFC is missing, provide clear error message with instructions
      - If RFC exists but status is not APPROVED, block changes and indicate required status
      - If RFC format is invalid, block changes and indicate required format
      - Error messages must include link to RFC template and process documentation
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.enforcement.error_messages
    description: |
      Error messages for RFC violations must be clear and actionable.
      - Indicate which file requires an RFC
      - Provide RFC template location
      - Explain RFC creation process
      - Link to RFC documentation
      - Show example RFC number format
      - Indicate required RFC status
    severity: error

  - id: rfc.workflow.creation
    description: |
      RFC creation workflow must be supported.
      - Developers can create RFCs using the template
      - RFCs can be in DRAFT status during creation
      - RFCs must be completed before setting status to APPROVED
      - RFCs must be added to RFC_INDEX.md
      - RFC numbering must follow sequential format
    severity: warning

  - id: rfc.workflow.implementation
    description: |
      RFC implementation tracking must be maintained.
      - RFC status should be updated to IMPLEMENTED when changes are complete
      - Implementation date should be recorded
      - RFC should remain in index for historical reference
      - Related RFCs should be cross-referenced
    severity: warning

examples:
  - description: "RFC validation check"
    language: markdown
    code: |
      Before editing `mavaia_core/brain/base_module.py`:
      
      1. Check if RFC exists in `.cursor/rules/governance/RFC/`
      2. Validate RFC format matches template
      3. Check RFC status is APPROVED
      4. Verify RFC is listed in RFC_INDEX.md
      5. If all checks pass, allow edit
      6. If any check fails, block edit with error message

  - description: "RFC error message format"
    language: text
    code: |
      ERROR: Changes to core architecture file require approved RFC
      
      File: mavaia_core/brain/base_module.py
      Required: RFC in APPROVED status
      
      To create an RFC:
      1. Copy template: .cursor/rules/governance/RFC/RFC_TEMPLATE.md
      2. Create file: .cursor/rules/governance/RFC/RFC-2025-XXX-Title.md
      3. Complete all required sections
      4. Add to RFC_INDEX.md
      5. Set status to APPROVED
      
      See: .cursor/rules/governance/RFC/README.md for details

references:
  - RFC Template: .cursor/rules/governance/RFC/RFC_TEMPLATE.md
  - RFC Index: .cursor/rules/governance/RFC/RFC_INDEX.md
  - RFC Documentation: .cursor/rules/governance/RFC/README.md
  - Architecture Rules: .cursor/rules/engineering/architecture_rules.mdc
